I know this feeling.

In my experience, it felt like,
. Being deceived by a stranger to go to a place alone.
. Being suddenly and violently held hostage.
. Being subjected to vicious torture such that you need a period of time to come to terms with what has just happened to you. But then always being subjected again before the mental toxin used to subdue you can subside enough for you to coherently take any action.
. The tactics of
Gaslighting,
Blame shifting,
Rage,
Triangulation,
Future faking,
Projection can be compared to straps used to tie you onto a bed, and your attempts to be reasonable to a stripping down of all your clothes until an extremely bewildered and frightened you feels completely naked and vulnerable.

. Then the callousness and disregard for your endless pleas for it to stop then realising there is no intention from this person to stop. That like a wild or rabbied animal, this person is proceeding to feed on your fear, pain, dispair and demise without any chance of considering your objections and lack of concent is the most diabolical experience you will have.

comment: Am I the only one that can‚Äôt stop looking at his bandages finger knowing what she did to him. He can‚Äôt stop bringing it to his face. The psychology of that is : he knows the camera is there. He‚Äôs glanced directly into it several times and then puts his hand to his mouth knowing the finger is extended, that it will be seen. He looks to her multiple times as if expecting her to say or do something especially since her grip on his hand just off camera seems to be keeping him in one spot and she‚Äôs standing unnecessarily close even for a wife. She‚Äôs looking around in an unnatural manner snd her smile seems fixed upon her as if there‚Äôs more beneath it somehow. He‚Äôs also stuttering more than usual snd his words are slurred more than usual. It makes wonder if she‚Äôs been dosing him again with ‚Äú Xanax‚Äù or if this is just his unnerved he is by her physical presence. I don‚Äôt think he‚Äôs necessarily afraid of her. But he seems concerned that she‚Äôs unwell. Like she might be high herself and may start randomly speaking. He‚Äôs very preoccupied by her presence than doing the interview. This all suggests that he‚Äôs subconsciously or maybe deliberately trying to get help. This seems like one if the first times since his injury that they are making a public appearance together. He calls her ‚Äúhis girl‚Äù and seems to be concerned of her reaction to his word choice as if she might refute it right there on the spot in front if the cameras or that it‚Äôs going to turn into something later as it often does. comment:
You've just seen a textbook narcissist and a textbook empath. Narcissists always prey on emphaths and enjoy seeing them insecure or  in pain, fear or shame. They appear to be very confident, can be very good-looking (or very smart), full of themselves, loving all the attention. The body language will tell you everything. She is staring at him like a lion at his prey, looking down upon him, controlling him and enjoying him being uncomfortable around her. 

I've dated a narcissist and manipulator too. He loved to see me insecure/uncomfortable, too. He knew I am insecure about my jaw (mild overbite) and I told him I'm about to have a jaw surgery (a HUGE mistake, never tell your partner about your insecurities). He knew it and he would stare at my face (not with "I adore you" look but with "I'm watching you and enjoying to see you uncomfortable" kind of look), would record videos with his phone directed at my face although he knew I was very uncomfortable about my profile (not talking about how many times he took pics of me without my permission or awareness) although I told him I didn't like it and then showed me those pics and played those videos to me and had the exact kind of smile on his face (seeing me insecure and uncomfortable on the videos) as Amber in this video. He was 50, I was 21, he was fat and had acne scars all over his back and face and I NEVER EVER made fun of him and used his own insecurities against him. He also knew that I was growing up without my father and that he didn't care about me, didn't send my mom money. He used all my weaknesses against me and treated me just as my dad (was very cheap with me, if we weren't together physically, he acted as if I don't exist). He is very smart, helps many strangers, he's a volunteer and this is how I was fooled, I thought he's a good person and must be a good partner.

She even asked me "even if I was to stab you in 'self defense' who do you think the cops would believe you as a man or me?". She even started fake crying with a knife pointed at my stomach while I was doing dishes and started talking to me as if she was speaking to cops afterwards.. saying things  in a sobbing voice like "he was coming at me and I didn't know what to do".

I then planned my escape that weekend afterwards, and moved out.. bought a gun (carry it on me 24/7) and have never looked back. But all I remember thinking all the time is there's women out there who are this crazy, abusive and hide that they think this way. They will hurt or threaten anyone to get what they want.

Still to this day my current wife tells me I have issues trusting people (like friends and family). We even reflected and it took me about a year or two to properly fall asleep overnight in the same bed together since we've started. I always tell her you would too after what I've dealt with.

comment:
Celebrities frighten me. When I was five, I had a big crush on Bobby Brady. A huge little girl crush. You know the kind of crush‚Äîwhen you can‚Äôt bear to even look at the beloved because the feelings are too big.  Anyway, one day when I was five, I was playing ‚ÄúSand Castles‚Äù in a park with a little boy my age while my mom talked with his mom. My mom beckoned to me and I went. She said, ‚ÄúDo you know who that little boy is? He‚Äôs your TV friend from the Brady Bunch and this is his mommy.‚Äù I was so frightened and upset‚Äî my mother tells me‚Äîthat I burst into tears, then hid behind a garbage can and threw up. She had to take me home.

So here‚Äôs me now‚Äîa survivor of domestic violence‚Äî48 years later, Hoovering YouTube for distraction, stumbling on to this post. I can tell you unequivocally, and without a trace of nausea or shame, that poor man is a domestic violence victim/survivor. It is heart wrenching to see. And all but impossible to fabricate. 

Johnny Depp, I wouldn‚Äôt have to puke in terror if ever you and I played Sand Castle. I can‚Äôt imagine what it would be like to go through that kind of crazy making, soul stealing abuse in public. Most people wear a mask‚Äîthe ‚ÄúI‚Äôm fine‚Äù ‚Äúit‚Äôs just another junket/red carpet/photo op‚Äù mask‚Äîwhen they‚Äôre deep in the weeds of domestic abuse. You‚Äôre still PRESENT. How? How did you do that? It would have been excruciating. The cognitive dissonance alone could drive you over the edge. So I‚Äôm writing this, basically, to say I see you, your integrity is palpable to me at least. And I say that as a woman scared to death of celebrity. My heart really and truly goes out to you. Thank you for staying authentic and true in the middle of the shit storm. Believe that those of us who have eyes, SEE.

Oh, please... People "seeing" things in this video, that's just ridiculous. She may have been physical at times too, but he was the abuser. There's abuse and then there's something called "reactive abuse".
The physical violence is the last to come in a long row of verbal and mental abuse. There's a point where a victim of verbal and mental abuse finally lashes out and can become violent after years of abuse.
"She's got no proof he abused her", for fuck's sake. That's the deal with verbal/mental abuse - there's no way to prove it, it's just word against word.
She wasn't the abuser, smh.

comment:
I don't want to be a person who throws alcohol and drugs under the bus but... 
Look at him when he was with Vanessa, during interviews and premiere. He was not drunk, he was not talking like he's talking in this video. Here, he's obviously kinda drunk. I don't know to what degree, but he is. Which is something he healed from with Vanessa Paradis when they started their family and all. There is a difference between recreational drug like pot for a party or in the intimacy of your house, and *this* and this never happened before Amber Heard. I mean, even with Winona Ryder or Kate Moss during his "chaotic years" he seemed more "clean" than when he was with Amber. Like?? On top of that, it looks like he didn't even shower or wash his hair? I'm sorry, I know Johnny has this way of having his own style, but it was always a "clean" style, it was stylish and different but it was badass because it was perfectly measured and clean. Here, it looks like he just put a suit and whatever. And the contrast is even bigger now that he's divorced her and we still see him at premiers and in press conferences. It's not "he drinks because he has social anxiety" no no no. Look at the Crimes of Grindelwald premiere, Johnny was very very nervous in this one, and yet, he's still better than he's on this video! Look at the press conference for Minamata! Day and night. Johnny never NEEDED to drink before a press conference before Amber Heard. Look at, idk his premieres for POTC1 or any big movie that happened BEFORE Amber. He's sober in these! He's nervous and shy here and there yes, but sober! He was especially nervous for Talk Shows, like David Letterman, Ellen and all: yes he was uncomfortable and all, but NOT DRUNK! There is a difference in everything: his looks, his demeanor, his attitude, his voice, and all that is attached to AMBER and not "Johnny being a drunk and a drug addict".

comment: This is Japan, the movie is "Mortdecai", and Amber Heard had a fight with Mr. Depp severe enough that he missed a news conference!  How did Mr. Depp explain?  "I was attacked yesterday morning by a very rarely seen or experienced animal called the chupacabra.  I fought with it for hours.  They are very persistent, very mean, and I'm pretty sure it came in my suitcase.  I threw him off the twenty-third floor.  So we'll never see him again.  Thank you for understanding."  If only we had known what he was going through.  For "chupacabra" read "Amber Heard", and we *wish* it had been thrown off the twenty-third floor, and we never had to see it again!  This would be around the time that Mr. Depp would send his exasperated text messages to Mr. Bettany, trying to vent his frustration over the abuse, the manipulation, and Ms. Heard's desire to totally control him.  At least he had a friend that understood what was going on, and how much pain he was in.  Does the victim of domestic abuse have the right to *privately* vent to his best friend?  I should hope so.  As a survivor of narcissistic abuse, no one who hasn't suffered abuse has the right to judge.

comment:
I'm just now finding this video but I notice so many things that suggest he's completely terrified of her. He keeps shifting his gaze and turning his head to the left as if he's watching her out of his peripheral vision. That's definitely something I would do if I was around someone I didn't trust.  He can't stand still the entire time. He starts pulling at his collar which suggests he is very nervous, possibly even feels threatened. It almost seems like he's trying to slowly move away from her and keep some distance between them. At one point she gets right up against him and he starts fidgeting and leans away from her. She seems to indicate something to him with her eyes and he looks down and starts fidgeting again.
I also watched the security guard in the back who keeps looking around at the crowd the entire time until Johnny uses the words "out of control" then he turns around and seems to be listening closely to what Johnny says. 
Meanwhile, Amber's completely disconnected from the interview and seems to only be there to keep Johnny "in line" and make sure he doesn't say anything. At no point does her body language ever portray her as the victim who is deathly afraid of Johnny.Her body language alone portrays her as cold and abusive. In fact, she almost seems to enjoy how nervous he is. I see no love in her eyes when she looks at him. 

I saw someone mention that he seems intoxicated but to me he just seems extremely nervous and scared. Sometimes the fear is paralyzing and it can be hard to speak in the presence of your abuser. He's trying his best to answer the questions and be present but you can tell his mind is elsewhere. You can just see the pain and sadness in his eyes. I really hope he gets the justice he deserves.

comment:
I really don't know who to believe, and ultimately couldn't care that much either way.


But

"Johnny Depp looking uneasy around abuser Amber Heard"

Based on  the title, the uploader has clearly already made up their mind on who they think the guilty party is, and has drawn their own conclusions from the body language in the video. The uploader says he was saying "stop" but it not very clear.   They clearly had an exchange but we don't know for sure what the context of it was.

One can only speculate or assume, based on what they think they heard phonetically, or in this case wanted to hear.

Maybe they were going through hard times relationship wise, hence the apparent awkwardness, but it's pure speculation that it was due to fear or nervousness on the part of Depp; and intimidation on the part of Amber.

But people watch the video with that context and interpretation in mind, and see what the uploader sees.

If the video had been titled 

"Johnny Depp tweaking from drug use during red carpet event"

Would people even have assumed it was from being uncomfortable around or scared in the presence of his wife? Especially, if they and the uploader supported Amber.

I've seen plenty of interviews with Depp w/o Amber present, where he has acted like this or similar.

As if he's uncomfortable in his own skin, or just doesn't do interviews well.

But people will believe what they want, or what they are told to believe.

comment: When I heard the accusations about him hitting her I honestly didn‚Äôt want to believe it. I don‚Äôt believe it, I kept saying if he did that I can‚Äôt support him ever again but I want too. Like I said I believe he is telling the truth and 100% think she‚Äôs been the abusive one. Remember abuse isn‚Äôt always physical. And tbh I think more women abuse their partners than men, it just won‚Äôt always been physical. But everything I‚Äôve heard has been all her, not him, I love Johnny depp so much. Honestly he was my crush when I was younger and my mums too ‚ù§Ô∏è I had a poster of captain jack sparrow above my bed and I would put lipstick on just before bed to kiss if every night. I know that‚Äôs sad, but I was like 7, 8 or 9 and I was fan girling so hard. I loved him in sweeny Todd and Charlie and the chocolate factory.  Then when I was older I watched blow. There‚Äôs more I promise I‚Äôm just half asleep. I‚Äôm glad people aren‚Äôt automatically picking her side because of the me too movement or the sexist shit of him being a man and her being a woman. I‚Äôve been a victim of sexual abuse aswell and physical and mental. You can throw in financial abuse aswell if you want. Yes I am a woman but I‚Äôve seen men go through it too. My partners little brother (17/18) was in an abusive relationship for over a year and we all tried to tell him, she did hit him, not only that but she manipulated him, kept tabs on him. She would try bolistic for no reason.  She would pick fights for no reason, and yes sometimes it was his fault but the was she spoke to him and what it was doing TO him, he was punching walls, hitting himself, throwing his phone, I was living with them and my little girl and she was picking up bad words and throwing stuff when she was angry and she was hitting herself, I couldn‚Äôt bare to see her like that. His mum tried to speak to him, it caused a huge riff in the family. But she was his first love and real relationship, it was hard for him to let go, not pick up the phone. We told him if she gets to much hang up on her. Let her be the one to apologise. But eventually he did end it and he was done. I was so happy for him, I kept talking to him and so did my brother in law who had been through the same thing. Just because she isn‚Äôt hitting you ( which we later found out she did) doesn‚Äôt mean it‚Äôs not toxic, we didn‚Äôt want him to use the word abuse. Also another one. A boy I work with he is 15, where I live the legal age is 16 instead of 18 like in America. He slept with a 29 year old woman, now I want to add, she knew his real age at the time. They weren‚Äôt in a bar or club. She was at her mothers house which is his next door neighbour. She also is married and has children, some of Which walked in while it happened, I also want to add it didn‚Äôt happen once that night it happened a few times. The boy I work with doesn‚Äôt see it as a big deal, but he is under the age of concent it doesn‚Äôt matter if he wanted it or not. comment: I've been with abusive partners and it's overwhelmingly clear to me from this that she is the abuser. Not only that, but Johnny comes across as a gentle, caring man who got roped into her bullshit and manipulations. Ive heard the depositions and it sounds like he covered for her in instances when she was violent towards him--to me that shows that he's so caring that he tries understand someone who is abusing him and avoid further conflict with her. Unfortunately it's very clear that Amber Heard is playing by a different set of rules--she's not motivated by compassion or connection or understanding but wanting to dominate and control and stir up drama--and that's something very hard for a genuinely caring and good-hearted person to comprehend, which means it's hard for the victim to recognize. The way she regards him and other people in this clip is chilling--she seems to have one hand on him to be in control and she just looks fake and manipulative when smiling, almost surveying the area as if to keep up a mask to other people. Also he clearly seems disturbed by how she's acting mad and he looks worried about what's going on (which she's oblivious to) but yet continues the interview trying to be as kind as possible to the interviewer. Genuine victims of abuse can go through hell and yet still somehow maintain their kindness and patience for others, it's honestly astounding and I'm 100% sure that is Johnny Depp in this situation

comment:
0:02 Amber pulls herself closer to Johnny, maybe she's trying to be in camera or act affectionate. Johnny said 'Stop' with a serious face. Amber responded with 'Huh?' then trying to get even closer to Johnny and pretend she didn't hear him.
0:05 Johnny was upset and said to her again  'Stop' and has a slight shake of the head muttering 'No no no', kinda like shaking off his frustration but in a gentle, non-aggresive way. 
0:21 He said 'My girl and I...' to include her in the conversation. But the next time she's on camera she doesn't seem interested at all in the conversation and...
0:48 In fact, Amber proceeds to looks around smugly searching and posing for other cameras nearby while Johnny is continuing the interview.
1:31 She looks back at the interviewer again, but doesn't seem genuine, almost like just posing for the sake of it, while Johnny is keeping eye contact and listening to the Interviewer's questions.
2:18 He looked for her approval and asked 'Can we go',  she smugly answered 'Go, please'. 
2:21 He said 'Thank you so much' in English then 'Arigatou (Thank you)' in Japanese to the Reporter, very soft and gentle.
Notice how Johnny actually wants to have a good, genuine chat with the Interviewers and how respectful he is by constantly making eye contact, using engaging language, putting himself into the interviewer's culture and formed a mutual connection in those brief minutes; while Amber's eyes and smiles all seem rather fake and off, as if she's only there to soullessly pose around for herself. It really says a lot about their personalities. Overall... Uneasy indeed. #JusticeforJohnnyDepp
